WEBVTT

00:07.007 --> 00:09.009
[theme music playing]

00:20.812 --> 00:27.277
<i>♪ Where in the world</i>
<i>Is Carmen Sandiego? ♪</i>

00:30.739 --> 00:32.741
<i>♪ Sandiego ♪</i>

00:43.668 --> 00:50.675
<i>♪ Where in the world</i>
<i>Is Carmen Sandiego? ♪</i>

00:58.516 --> 01:00.143
[Player in Australian accent]
G'day, mate!

01:00.935 --> 01:04.439
Crikey!
Australia's one big country!

01:05.023 --> 01:06.357
[Carmen] <i>That's some accent.</i>

01:06.733 --> 01:08.068
[normal accent] Been practicing.

01:08.151 --> 01:11.196
I wanted to brush up on the latest leg
of your nonstop tour, Red.

01:12.113 --> 01:15.283
So, what's playing at the famous
Sydney Opera House tonight?

01:16.117 --> 01:18.870
Something VILE won't care to see
if they decide to show.

01:19.662 --> 01:20.538
<i>Carmen.</i>

01:20.622 --> 01:22.791
[Player] <i>Well, good sign or bad omen?</i>

01:22.874 --> 01:25.627
Depends.
Don't most operas have tragic endings?

01:25.794 --> 01:28.338
Like I ever sat through one.
But check it out.

01:29.047 --> 01:30.215
This Carmen's a gypsy,

01:30.298 --> 01:33.426
she likes to wear red
and she hangs out with smugglers.

01:33.510 --> 01:35.345
[Carmen] <i>Guess I have a new BFF.</i>

01:35.637 --> 01:37.639
[orchestral music playing]

01:50.777 --> 01:53.696
[Player] <i>So, what's going on</i>
<i>with Carmen, Carmen?</i>

01:54.656 --> 01:56.699
[Carmen] Nothing suspicious so far.

01:57.575 --> 02:00.703
If a VILE operative's here,
they have yet to show their face.

02:01.579 --> 02:02.539
[Gray] You there!

02:02.956 --> 02:03.790
Scratch that.

02:04.124 --> 02:05.667
What are you doing back here?

02:05.875 --> 02:06.709
You first.

02:07.710 --> 02:09.337
What? I'm working.

02:09.671 --> 02:11.798
I know. "Lights out, baby."

02:11.965 --> 02:14.217
Come on, Gray,
what job are you pulling tonight?

02:14.676 --> 02:16.302
First, it's "Gray-ham,"

02:16.386 --> 02:19.639
and second, since electricians
don't seem to intimidate you,

02:19.722 --> 02:22.600
I'll be more than happy
to have security escort you out.

02:22.892 --> 02:23.768
Wait, what?

02:24.185 --> 02:26.729
You don't expect me to believe
this innocent act, do you?

02:27.230 --> 02:30.233
No wristband, no backstage access.

02:30.316 --> 02:31.442
I don't make the rules.

02:33.069 --> 02:36.239
You really don't remember me?

02:37.866 --> 02:40.827
Fashion statement aside, mate,
you'd be hard to forget.

02:42.537 --> 02:45.832
If there is a next time,
I promise not to make that mistake again.

02:46.166 --> 02:49.127
Guess you just, uh, remind me
of someone I used to know.

02:50.336 --> 02:52.046
I have one of those faces.

02:52.130 --> 02:53.089
Enjoy the show.

02:56.843 --> 02:59.345
[woman singing
"L'amour est un oiseau rebelle"]

03:00.430 --> 03:01.264
Player, did you...?

03:01.347 --> 03:04.642
Yeah, I heard all of it.
So, what's your old classmate's game?

03:04.976 --> 03:08.605
Not sure he has one.
He had no idea who I was.

03:09.105 --> 03:10.648
What did they do to him?

03:10.982 --> 03:13.776
Red, our intel indicates
a VILE operative's

03:13.860 --> 03:15.737
inside the opera house right now.

03:16.070 --> 03:19.574
Crackle worked there as an electrician
before you knew him at VILE Academy.

03:19.657 --> 03:20.825
He knows the layout.

03:20.909 --> 03:24.287
<i>-How can you be sure he isn't playing you?</i>
-Besides the look in his eye?

03:24.913 --> 03:27.790
I'm staring at another VILE operative
right now.

03:28.666 --> 03:32.295
It's Le Chevre, and he's brought
some sort of shiny new toy.

03:33.254 --> 03:36.049
[aria continues]

03:42.263 --> 03:43.097
[shouts]

03:43.431 --> 03:44.307
Carmen?

03:45.225 --> 03:46.893
Do you mean me or the opera?

03:47.769 --> 03:48.603
Hup, hup.

03:49.479 --> 03:51.022
What have we here?

03:54.025 --> 03:55.026
Hup!

03:55.568 --> 03:56.653
[both grunt]

03:59.072 --> 03:59.906
[grunts]

04:02.116 --> 04:03.660
[clanging in rhythm to music]

04:03.993 --> 04:06.162
[aria continues]

04:18.925 --> 04:20.593
[soft squeaking]

04:20.760 --> 04:22.595
This will do.

04:25.890 --> 04:28.476
[aria continues]

04:36.484 --> 04:37.860
-[thuds]
-[Carmen grunts]

04:39.320 --> 04:41.531
[grunting]

04:42.490 --> 04:44.659
[pulsing]

04:44.742 --> 04:46.661
[aria continues, muffled]

04:47.704 --> 04:48.663
[crackling]

04:48.746 --> 04:50.665
[electricity buzzing]

04:53.376 --> 04:55.420
-[aria continues normally]
-[chuckles]

05:01.009 --> 05:03.469
-[song ends]
-[cheering and applause]

05:07.432 --> 05:08.975
What was that all about?

05:09.267 --> 05:13.271
Player, I have no idea what I just heard,
but it had to be a VILE note.

05:13.354 --> 05:14.981
<i>Good thing I was in record mode.</i>

05:15.064 --> 05:16.899
Let's play it back and find out.

05:16.983 --> 05:19.319
[woman singing
"L'amour est un oiseau rebelle"]

05:20.486 --> 05:23.573
[Le Chevre humming
"L'amour est un oiseau rebelle"]

05:24.115 --> 05:26.534
<i>Phase one accomplished, Dr. Bellum.</i>

05:26.993 --> 05:29.412
<i>The seed has been planted.</i>

05:29.662 --> 05:31.831
Superb. But skip the singing.

05:31.914 --> 05:33.374
You bleat like a goat.

05:33.833 --> 05:36.669
Oh, and did you happen to see
my dear boy?

05:36.753 --> 05:39.505
<i>El Topo?</i>
<i>He is tunneling, according to plan.</i>

05:39.589 --> 05:41.132
Not your dear boy.

05:41.507 --> 05:43.301
Mine. Crackle.

05:43.634 --> 05:45.470
Such a fine student.

05:45.636 --> 05:47.388
I shall never forget him.

05:47.722 --> 05:51.392
<i>And he shall never remember us.</i>
[giggles]

05:51.476 --> 05:53.561
[Bellum] I would not make light,
Le Chevre.

05:53.895 --> 05:55.688
Slip up on the job like he did,

05:55.772 --> 05:58.441
and I could be draining your brainpan
someday.

05:59.358 --> 06:00.568
<i>Uh... </i>[clears throat]

06:00.985 --> 06:03.613
<i>And on the topic of former students,</i>

06:03.696 --> 06:07.784
<i>a certain Carmen made a guest appearance</i>
<i>at tonight's performance of </i>Carmen.

06:08.242 --> 06:12.872
Then I do hope she had the opportunity
to hear my remix.

06:13.998 --> 06:15.958
[Bellum's voice] <i>Launch the Boomerang.</i>

06:16.042 --> 06:17.585
<i>Launch the Boomerang.</i>

06:17.668 --> 06:20.922
<i>It's Dr. Saira Bellum.</i>
<i>Not exactly the voice of an angel.</i>

06:21.005 --> 06:24.258
Concealed in the sound wave projected
from Goat Boy's device.

06:24.342 --> 06:26.260
Most likely a subliminal message,

06:26.344 --> 06:28.721
designed to make the listener
follow its command.

06:28.805 --> 06:32.100
<i>As in that's one tune</i>
<i>I don't want stuck in my head.</i>

06:32.183 --> 06:34.018
As in let's hope it isn't.

06:34.352 --> 06:35.686
You were at the opera, too.

06:35.770 --> 06:37.313
<i>Except I wasn't the target.</i>

06:37.688 --> 06:40.274
<i>I don't have a boomerang to launch,</i>
<i>whatever that means.</i>

06:40.441 --> 06:41.901
Thought you'd never ask.

06:41.984 --> 06:45.530
There's only one launchable boomerang
I could find, a rocket,

06:45.613 --> 06:48.032
and it happens to be right there
in Australia.

06:48.116 --> 06:50.368
It's owned by HelioGem,
a private company

06:50.451 --> 06:52.995
with a four billion-dollar
space flight contract.

06:53.079 --> 06:56.207
So I poked around the data
in VILE's hard drive, and guess what.

06:56.290 --> 06:59.752
Your former teachers have been trying
to get a piece of the business, too.

06:59.919 --> 07:02.255
And all this has what to do with an opera?

07:02.338 --> 07:06.092
<i>My thought exactly, which is why I hacked</i>
<i>into the opera house box office</i>

07:06.175 --> 07:08.261
<i>and HelioGem's employee database.</i>

07:08.427 --> 07:10.221
And one name in common turned up.

07:11.264 --> 07:16.686
Dr. Jeanine Dennam, lead engineer
of the Boomerang and avid opera buff.

07:16.936 --> 07:20.189
Guess who purchased a ticket
for tonight's performance of <i>Carmen</i>.

07:20.773 --> 07:24.485
So Bellum's subliminal message
was directed at Dr. Dennam.

07:24.652 --> 07:25.486
You got it.

07:25.570 --> 07:28.281
And I imagine whatever tune
happened to be playing at that time

07:28.364 --> 07:30.741
would trigger her
into obeying the command.

07:30.825 --> 07:33.744
I just can't figure out what
the Villains International League of Evil

07:33.828 --> 07:36.289
would have to gain by forcing her
to launch her own rocket.

07:36.956 --> 07:38.124
Considering it's VILE,

07:38.207 --> 07:41.919
I say we hightail it to HelioGem ASAP
and see if we can't find out.

07:42.086 --> 07:43.713
[Player] <i>Easier said than done, Red.</i>

07:43.796 --> 07:47.049
<i>The HelioGem base is pretty deep</i>
<i>in harsh outback territory.</i>

07:47.341 --> 07:50.011
<i>-I'd recommend finding a guide.</i>
-[Carmen] Found one.

07:50.303 --> 07:53.723
[Player] <i>Wait, Crackle again?</i>
<i>You're playing with a live wire, Red.</i>

07:53.806 --> 07:56.809
Don't forget, he once tried
to electrocute you on a train.

07:57.310 --> 07:59.061
On direct orders from VILE,

07:59.145 --> 08:01.731
whom he doesn't seem to know
even exists anymore.

08:01.814 --> 08:02.648
[switch clicks]

08:04.108 --> 08:07.445
[humming
"L'amour est un oiseau rebelle"]

08:09.780 --> 08:12.492
Hey, I remember you.

08:12.783 --> 08:14.869
Ol' Red Sneakeroo.

08:15.077 --> 08:15.995
Good memory.

08:16.996 --> 08:17.955
Not really.

08:19.165 --> 08:22.210
So, looking to get backstage
for an autograph?

08:22.919 --> 08:27.757
No. To the outback for some sightseeing.
Thought you could be my guide.

08:27.965 --> 08:31.093
I wish. Something fried
the soundboard tonight.

08:31.177 --> 08:33.679
I have to pull an early morning shift
to troubleshoot.

08:33.846 --> 08:36.641
You mentioned having a bad memory.
Why is that?

08:36.974 --> 08:40.102
Well, I-- I kind of messed up on the job
a while back,

08:40.186 --> 08:42.313
got a little "jolt," as we sparkies say.

08:42.563 --> 08:45.566
Complete blackout, long hospital stay,
blah, blah. [chuckles]

08:45.650 --> 08:49.654
There's more than an entire year
of my life I can't remember.

08:49.904 --> 08:51.072
A whole year?

08:51.364 --> 08:53.074
I'd say I'm lucky to have my job back

08:53.157 --> 08:55.868
if electrician weren't
such a dangerous occupation.

08:56.160 --> 08:57.954
Oh, I can think of worse ones.

08:58.162 --> 09:00.331
Is this the address of an outback guide?

09:00.414 --> 09:02.333
A good guide's easy to find online.

09:02.667 --> 09:05.753
This is the address
of my favorite café in Sydney.

09:05.962 --> 09:09.298
I'll be there Friday night
at 8:00 p.m. You?

09:10.508 --> 09:12.718
Let's see if I make it back
from my tour in one piece.

09:14.512 --> 09:16.305
Hey, I never got your name!

09:16.973 --> 09:17.848
Carmen.

09:19.141 --> 09:20.726
[laughs]

09:20.810 --> 09:22.520
You are a cheeky one.

09:23.521 --> 09:26.566
[Player] The outback,
it may sound like someone's backyard,

09:26.649 --> 09:30.570
but it's a huge wilderness that covers
more than 80 percent of Australia.

09:30.653 --> 09:33.656
That's over half the size
of the US or China.

09:33.739 --> 09:36.534
[Carmen] <i>Tons of room to roam</i>
<i>for all the local critters,</i>

09:36.617 --> 09:39.620
<i>like dingoes, crocodiles and kangaroos.</i>

09:39.704 --> 09:41.289
[Player] Yo, what's up, joey?

09:41.372 --> 09:44.458
[Carmen] <i>Smack in the middle</i>
<i>of all that real estate sits Ayers Rock.</i>

09:44.542 --> 09:45.376
[Player] Whoa!

09:45.459 --> 09:49.505
What kind of <i>rock</i> is two miles long
and over 1,000 feet tall?

09:49.589 --> 09:52.550
[Carmen] <i>One the Aboriginal people</i>
<i>who live there consider sacred.</i>

09:52.633 --> 09:54.302
<i>Their name for it is Uluru.</i>

09:54.760 --> 09:56.095
[Player] Just be careful, Red.

09:56.178 --> 09:59.557
Like I said, there's some pretty harsh
terrain out there in the outback.

10:00.391 --> 10:02.393
[didgeridoo music playing]

10:16.866 --> 10:19.285
I hear kangaroos are wicked good boxers.

10:19.368 --> 10:23.205
-Ever go a few rounds with one, Miro?
-I can't say that I have.

10:23.289 --> 10:25.166
Oh, well, how about a crocodile?

10:25.249 --> 10:28.419
-Ever wrestle one of those?
-No, sorry.

10:28.502 --> 10:29.920
Ooh, what about koalas?

10:30.004 --> 10:32.465
Are they really as vicious
as everyone says they are?

10:32.548 --> 10:35.885
-Oh, no, wait. Is that dingoes?
-What about that rock, Zack?

10:35.968 --> 10:39.513
I'd shove it in your mouth to shut you up,
but I don't think it's big enough.

10:40.473 --> 10:42.892
-Uluru.
-Very good.

10:42.975 --> 10:48.564
The ground it occupies has been home
to my people for at least 22,000 years.

10:49.023 --> 10:50.441
We're on sacred land.

10:50.775 --> 10:51.651
That's right.

10:52.068 --> 10:54.236
-[Player] <i>Yo, Red.</i>
-Excuse me, Miro.

10:54.320 --> 10:55.196
[Player] <i>Good news.</i>

10:55.279 --> 10:57.740
Turns out HelioGem delayed the launch
of the Boomerang

10:57.823 --> 10:59.408
to do some serious repair work.

10:59.492 --> 11:00.785
The rocket's defective.

11:00.868 --> 11:02.745
<i>So there's no launch to stop.</i>

11:02.828 --> 11:04.872
<i>Boy, will VILE be surprised.</i>

11:05.456 --> 11:08.334
-No, this is their plan.
<i>-What?</i>

11:08.709 --> 11:10.753
Miro, how far are we from HelioGem?

11:10.836 --> 11:13.297
It's not too far
outside the park boundaries.

11:13.464 --> 11:16.675
Player, what happens if a defective rocket
prematurely launches?

11:16.759 --> 11:19.720
[Player] <i>Depends on the defect.</i>
<i>It might not achieve orbit.</i>

11:19.804 --> 11:21.680
Or explode before it reaches
the atmosphere,

11:21.764 --> 11:24.183
raining debris down
on sacred Aboriginal land?

11:24.600 --> 11:28.104
The public outcry would be so great,
HelioGem would lose their contract.

11:28.354 --> 11:31.190
[Player] <i>Paving the way for VILE</i>
<i>to step in and take it over</i>

11:31.273 --> 11:35.194
<i>since they pulled strings to make it look</i>
<i>like HelioGem's incompetence was at fault.</i>

11:36.987 --> 11:39.281
We have to prevent
the desecration of Uluru.

11:39.907 --> 11:42.368
You aren't tourists, are you?

11:42.660 --> 11:45.204
We're rocket scientists.

11:50.376 --> 11:52.002
[Carmen] Divide and conquer, crew.

11:52.086 --> 11:53.587
We know the trigger's in the music.

11:53.671 --> 11:55.423
You two need to find Dr. Dennam

11:55.506 --> 11:58.384
and make sure she doesn't decide
she's in the mood to hear <i>Carmen.</i>

11:58.551 --> 11:59.718
We hear you, Carmen.

12:00.845 --> 12:02.721
Our boss, not the opera.

12:02.972 --> 12:06.642
And I'll see to it no one launches
the Boomerang until it's ready to soar.

12:08.310 --> 12:10.646
Player, let's steal some launch codes.

12:14.608 --> 12:16.402
[beeping]

12:32.585 --> 12:33.502
There she is!

12:34.879 --> 12:35.713
Oh, no!

12:39.300 --> 12:41.385
Dr. Jeanine Dennam, stop!

12:42.303 --> 12:43.137
Pardon?

12:43.637 --> 12:45.514
We're your new interns.

12:45.681 --> 12:46.557
You are?

12:46.891 --> 12:48.767
So, what you listening to, Doc?

12:48.851 --> 12:52.354
A podcast about exploring Proxima b.

12:52.730 --> 12:53.898
Not an opera?

12:54.064 --> 12:58.527
Goodness, I find opera far too distracting
when I'm working.

12:58.736 --> 12:59.570
[sighs]

12:59.653 --> 13:01.739
[laughing] Whoa!

13:01.822 --> 13:05.659
This guy says there's a second Earth
that might have aliens on it!

13:05.951 --> 13:08.078
We have got to visit this planet.

13:08.454 --> 13:10.539
[computer beeping]

13:11.749 --> 13:13.626
And I'm in.

13:15.544 --> 13:18.047
Good thing, Red,
because it would take me hours to hack

13:18.130 --> 13:20.299
through the HelioGem firewalls
from where I sit.

13:22.676 --> 13:24.512
Whoa, that's a big button.

13:24.678 --> 13:25.930
[Player] <i>System default.</i>

13:26.013 --> 13:28.182
<i>Once you delete the launch codes,</i>
<i>it'll retract.</i>

13:28.265 --> 13:31.602
<i>Until then, just don't press it,</i>
<i>whatever you do.</i>

13:37.024 --> 13:38.734
Are you ready, <i>mon ami?</i>

13:39.401 --> 13:43.781
Hold on to your horns, <i>mi amigo,</i>
for the show is about to begin.

13:45.658 --> 13:48.327
-[beeps]
-["L'amour est un oiseau rebelle" playing]

13:51.080 --> 13:53.040
[aria blaring over speakers]

13:54.416 --> 13:55.251
[beeps]

13:56.043 --> 13:58.379
[aria blaring over speakers]

13:58.462 --> 14:02.716
Then my colleagues found me huddled
in the corner of the laboratory, weeping.

14:02.800 --> 14:07.429
[sighs] Puccini never fails
to reduce me to tears.

14:08.097 --> 14:12.309
That was the day I decided the laboratory
is no place for opera.

14:12.393 --> 14:14.395
[aria blaring over speakers]

14:18.148 --> 14:20.609
Ah! I love Bizet!

14:20.901 --> 14:22.903
[aria continues]

14:25.030 --> 14:26.740
Launch the Boomerang.

14:27.491 --> 14:29.493
Launch the Boomerang.

14:29.994 --> 14:32.955
-[both] Uh-oh!
-We can't let her get to mission control.

14:33.414 --> 14:35.207
Launch the Boomerang.

14:35.291 --> 14:37.501
No Boomerangs this way,
that's for sure.

14:38.586 --> 14:40.379
Launch the Boomerang.

14:40.713 --> 14:42.673
What do you want to do that for anyway?

14:45.342 --> 14:47.177
Launch the Boomerang.

14:47.261 --> 14:49.221
You got some determination, Doc.

14:52.474 --> 14:54.351
Launch the Boomerang.

14:55.269 --> 14:57.813
All this talk about "lunch"
is making me hungry.

14:57.897 --> 14:59.106
[Ivy] Focus, Zack.

14:59.565 --> 15:01.734
Launch the Boomerang.

15:06.113 --> 15:08.157
Launch the Boomerang.

15:11.535 --> 15:13.746
The lab is totally no place for opera.

15:16.582 --> 15:19.084
-Launch the Boomerang.
-[beeps]

15:19.668 --> 15:22.087
-[muffled] Launch the Boomerang.
-[laughs] Oh!

15:22.171 --> 15:24.006
We did Carmen wicked proud.

15:24.465 --> 15:26.842
Our boss, not the opera.

15:27.092 --> 15:29.011
[beeping]

15:29.094 --> 15:30.638
[Player] <i>One more sequence</i>
<i>should do it.</i>

15:30.721 --> 15:32.681
-[aria continues]
-[beeps]

15:34.099 --> 15:35.601
[aria blaring over speakers]

15:40.648 --> 15:42.107
Launch the Boomerang.

15:42.983 --> 15:44.485
Launch the Boomerang.

15:45.402 --> 15:46.779
<i>Launch the Boomerang.</i>

15:47.321 --> 15:48.572
The subliminal message!

15:48.822 --> 15:50.199
<i>Red, snap out of it!</i>

15:50.699 --> 15:52.201
Launch the Boomerang.

15:52.785 --> 15:54.119
Launch the Boomerang.

15:54.203 --> 15:55.537
[beeps]

15:57.456 --> 16:00.417
-[Carmen] Launch the Boomerang.
-[male voice] <i>Launch sequence activated.</i>

16:00.501 --> 16:02.795
-[beeping]
<i>-Liftoff in T-minus three minutes.</i>

16:02.878 --> 16:04.296
Launch the Boomerang.

16:04.755 --> 16:06.715
[alarm blaring]

16:08.133 --> 16:10.177
[gas hissing]

16:13.389 --> 16:16.433
[distant alarm blaring]

16:17.434 --> 16:19.937
-Whoa! Sweet subwoofer.
-[phone ringing]

16:20.312 --> 16:23.273
-Player?
<i>-Guys, Carmen activated the rocket.</i>

16:23.357 --> 16:25.150
<i>It launches in less than three minutes!</i>

16:25.234 --> 16:27.277
-What?
-Carm went to the dark side?

16:27.444 --> 16:30.864
She's hypnotized, and she'll stay that way
as long as that music's playing.

16:31.657 --> 16:33.283
I've pinpointed the audio source.

16:33.367 --> 16:36.120
It's coming from a utility tunnel
under the facility.

16:36.286 --> 16:38.872
<i>You need to shut it down</i>
<i>so Carmen can snap to her senses.</i>

16:39.039 --> 16:40.833
<i>We need her to disable the rocket.</i>

16:40.916 --> 16:44.044
I can handle that last part.
Go axe a DJ, bro.

16:57.266 --> 16:59.018
[gas hissing]

16:59.101 --> 17:01.186
[alarm blaring]

17:01.311 --> 17:03.647
[Player] <i>Okay, Ivy, you'll need to get</i>
<i>to the control panel</i>

17:03.731 --> 17:05.024
<i>and remove the launch drive.</i>

17:05.774 --> 17:06.817
What control panel?

17:07.276 --> 17:09.737
<i>It's on the rocket's payload.</i>
<i>Top of the tower.</i>

17:11.613 --> 17:13.699
Ooh, that's really up there.

17:21.749 --> 17:23.709
Ninety seconds to launch.

17:27.671 --> 17:29.757
You cannot out-climb a goat!

17:31.842 --> 17:34.470
-[aria continues]
-[keyboard clicking]

17:36.472 --> 17:38.515
[in Australian accent]
Have you not heard the alert?

17:38.599 --> 17:40.684
-What alert?
-The dingo alert.

17:40.893 --> 17:42.770
The doggies are going wild out there.

17:43.228 --> 17:44.521
It's... it's the high notes.

17:44.605 --> 17:47.566
They, uh-- Gets them all crazed
and bloodthirsty!

17:47.900 --> 17:49.109
Do they come below ground?

17:49.318 --> 17:51.779
[chuckles] I'm a rocket scientist,
not a zookeeper.

17:51.862 --> 17:56.075
Oh, but, but they're out there,
and they mangled some French dude!

17:56.325 --> 17:57.242
Le Chevre!

18:01.705 --> 18:02.539
[music stops]

18:02.915 --> 18:04.374
Launch the Boomerang.

18:05.084 --> 18:06.335
-[music stops]
-[static buzzing]

18:06.418 --> 18:07.252
[sighs]

18:07.336 --> 18:08.879
[normal accent] Nails on a chalkboard.

18:08.962 --> 18:11.465
-Launch the Boomera--
-[alarm beeping]

18:11.840 --> 18:12.674
What?

18:16.095 --> 18:17.137
What have I done?

18:17.679 --> 18:20.516
Oh, boy. Oh, boy! Oh, boy!
Oh, boy! Oh, boy!

18:25.354 --> 18:27.189
[rumbling]

18:49.044 --> 18:51.046
[gasping]

18:51.213 --> 18:52.089
[growls]

18:54.007 --> 18:55.384
[beeping]

18:55.551 --> 18:56.426
[grunts]

18:57.594 --> 18:58.554
What? [grunts]

18:58.762 --> 18:59.721
Let go!

19:00.347 --> 19:01.181
[beeps]

19:01.557 --> 19:02.558
[both grunting]

19:03.058 --> 19:05.853
-Get out of my way!
-My face!

19:12.860 --> 19:13.694
[beeps]

19:21.285 --> 19:23.287
[both shouting, grunting]

19:26.874 --> 19:28.375
-Oh, boy.
-[horn honks]

19:28.458 --> 19:30.961
Le Chevre, it is safe to come down.

19:31.044 --> 19:32.713
The dingoes have all gone!

19:33.005 --> 19:34.631
What are you talking about?

19:35.257 --> 19:36.675
Enjoy the flight.

19:37.134 --> 19:38.427
-What?
-[grunts]

19:42.306 --> 19:44.057
You can't leave me here.

19:44.141 --> 19:45.601
I'm no space cadet.

19:46.602 --> 19:47.436
[beeps]

19:48.020 --> 19:49.479
[grunts, gasps]

19:50.480 --> 19:51.315
[beeps]

19:51.398 --> 19:54.234
[whimpering]

19:54.401 --> 19:56.320
[screaming]

19:57.112 --> 19:57.946
[clinks]

19:58.071 --> 19:59.656
[Ivy screaming]

19:59.823 --> 20:00.657
I've got you.

20:02.326 --> 20:03.785
[Ivy screams, groans]

20:05.495 --> 20:06.330
[beeps]

20:06.580 --> 20:08.290
[rocket powers down]

20:13.962 --> 20:14.880
[sighs]

20:21.220 --> 20:22.137
[both grunt]

20:22.221 --> 20:23.597
-[sighs]
-Good work, Ivy.

20:24.223 --> 20:25.432
[Ivy] Number two, huh?

20:25.891 --> 20:27.851
I think I just did that in my pants.

20:29.728 --> 20:32.356
-[orchestral music playing]
-[people chattering]

20:35.400 --> 20:37.527
[Player] <i>Remember, Red,</i>
<i>Crackle once tried to--</i>

20:37.611 --> 20:40.489
Turn out my lights
with a sizzle stick, I know, but...

20:40.864 --> 20:42.741
before he was Crackle, he was Gray.

20:42.991 --> 20:44.868
And Gray was like a big brother to me.

20:45.535 --> 20:49.665
I thought I lost him for good,
but this could be, I don't know...

20:50.374 --> 20:52.292
some sort of do-over?

20:53.085 --> 20:54.586
A second chance?

20:55.128 --> 20:59.383
[Player] <i>Okay, let's say that I buy</i>
<i>that Gray, Crackle, Graham, whoever,</i>

20:59.466 --> 21:02.094
<i>really is a happy electrician</i>
<i>with a bright future now.</i>

21:02.302 --> 21:05.013
We know Dr. Bellum's
into mind-control experiments.

21:05.097 --> 21:07.432
What if she played him
some opera music, too?

21:07.516 --> 21:10.519
What if VILE is waiting to see you
with him so they can flip a switch?

21:11.019 --> 21:14.564
<i>Bam! Instead of launching a rocket,</i>
<i>Crackle's crunching a Carmen.</i>

21:16.650 --> 21:18.110
You have a point, Player.

21:31.290 --> 21:33.166
I can't let VILE see me with him.

21:34.126 --> 21:36.670
But not for my safety, for his.

21:36.878 --> 21:38.547
[Player] <i>What? Why?</i>

21:38.630 --> 21:41.174
For whatever strange reason,
Gray has a fresh start now.

21:41.258 --> 21:45.554
And having Carmen Sandiego back
in his life would only complicate that.

21:51.643 --> 21:53.979
[Maelstrom] <i>My star student.</i>

21:55.480 --> 21:56.815
Thank you for coming.

21:57.899 --> 22:01.194
I was wondering
if you would be up for a certain task.

22:02.237 --> 22:06.533
Bring me the hat of Carmen Sandiego.

22:18.462 --> 22:20.839
I will take that as a "yes."

22:26.720 --> 22:29.014
[theme music playing]
